Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Tarrance Jovan Collins in court with attorney Valeria Lenise Taylor.  David T. Malone appeared for the State of Wisconsin.   Deputy court clerk: LMS.

Defendant has completed community service and is employed.

The defendant has complied with the Deferred Prosecution Agreement.
On motion of the state, the court amended the charge to Possession of THC, contrary to Wisconsin Statutes section(s) 961.41(3g)(e), a class U misdemeanor.   Court ordered entry of judgment of conviction to the amended charge.

Court sentenced defendant to serve 1 DAY in the House of Correction CONSECUTIVE to any sentence with credit for 1 day served; TIME SERVED DISPOSITION.

Court orders defendant to pay all cost, fees and surcharges 4/6/2016 or a civil judgment to be entered with tax intercept.  Bail on deposit to be applied if applicable.
